# BMF — the architecture of one engine, drawn from coordinates

> This is the **dream** — the architecture painted from the new center
> (coordinates, non-mutation, observation, grammar-as-data, BML superset,
> thin kernel) *before* looking at the current implementation. The
> reimplementation reconciles this picture with what the body already holds.
> Read it as a shape to meet, not a finished claim.

## The whole picture in one breath

BMF is **one recipe** that turns an input stream into output nodes:

```
input surface ──▶ Cursor ──▶ Match(grammar) ──▶ emit recipes ──▶ output NodeIDs
```

A **grammar** is a bag of **rules**. A rule is a **(Pattern, Template)** pair:
the Pattern says *what to match* in the stream, the Template says *what node to
emit*. The engine — `Match` — drives a Cursor through the grammar's rules and
interns a recipe per completed rule. The parse stack holds NodeIDs, never
mutable AST; backtracking is restoring an earlier stack-coordinate.

The move that closes the loop: **the meta-grammar is itself a grammar.** The
rules that parse grammar definitions emit Pattern / Template / Rule / Grammar
recipes — the very shapes `Match` consumes. So the whole compiler-compiler is
two applications of the *same* engine:

```
Match( meta_grammar,    Cursor(grammar_source) )  ──▶  content_grammar   # compile a grammar
Match( content_grammar, Cursor(input_stream)   )  ──▶  output_nodes      # run it on content
```

Nothing in the engine knows whether the grammar it is running is the
meta-grammar or a Python grammar or an audio grammar. The engine is fixed; the
grammar is data. That is the whole bet.

## The center this is drawn from

- **Nodes are coordinates.** Pattern, Template, Rule, Grammar, Cursor, and every
  emitted output node are all `NodeID(package, level, type, instance)`. Rule
  dispatch is an O(1) coordinate lookup, not a scan over a rule list.
- **Nothing mutates.** The parse stack is a sequence of NodeIDs; a rule that
  fails restores the prior stack coordinate. Two `Alt` branches share no
  writable state, so they may be matched in parallel — first success commits.
- **Observation condenses.** `Match(rule, cursor_pos)` is memoized by
  `(rule_coordinate, position)` — packrat parsing falls out of content-addressing
  for free. A hot rule condenses gas → water → ice; the JIT is that condensation
  applied to the engine's own hot loop.
- **Grammar is data, engine is code.** The only code is `Match` + the Cursor
  surfaces + the kernel primitives. Everything else — every rule of every
  grammar, including the meta-grammar — is cells on the lattice.
- **BML is the superset.** Templates emit into the universal BML/NUMS.Go shape
  vocabulary (`B_Function`, `R_Cond`, `R_Binary`, …), so `if` from any tongue
  lands on one coordinate. New expressive power lands in BML first.
- **The kernel stays thin.** Host surfaces (I/O, RAM, storage, socket), a set of
  primitives, intern/dedup, a JIT, and a framebuffer. No grammar logic in the
  kernel — ever.

## The shared vocabulary — blueprints every grammar uses

These Blueprints are the "class hierarchy." They are shared by the meta-grammar
**and** every content grammar; a grammar differs only in its rule-*data* and its
target output vocabulary. Generics are written `B_X⟨param⟩` — a Blueprint
parameterized by another Blueprint; instantiating a generic is just composing a
new Blueprint NodeID, so `Cursor⟨File⟩` and `Cursor⟨Socket⟩` are distinct
coordinates that share the `Cursor` category.

### Pattern blueprints — the matching side

```form
# A Pattern is anything that can consume some prefix of a Cursor and either
# fail or succeed (advancing the cursor + optionally binding captures).
form Pattern = ~Sum [                 # one category, several arms (a tagged union)
    Literal,                          # match an exact run of characters ("if", "+")
    Class,                            # match ONE character of a named class (digit, alpha)
    Run,                              # match a RUN of a class — what a lexer would scan, inline
    Ref,                              # call another rule by name (recursion)
    Seq,                              # all parts in order
    Alt,                              # first matching alternative  (parse-time `choose`)
    Opt,                              # zero or one
    Rep,                              # zero+ (optionally separated)  → binds a list
    Capture,                          # bind the consumed slice to a name
    Pred,                             # lookahead / guard, consumes nothing
    Str, Char, Num,                   # scannerless literal matchers — string / char / number, read
                                      # straight off the cursor (no lexer, no token stream)
    Infix,                            # precedence-climbing binary operators — operators as DATA
    Chain,                            # postfix-suffix fold — member / call / index / template-call / ++ --
    Ternary,                          # cond ? then : else
]

form Literal      = { chars: ~String }                        # an exact string of characters
form Class        = { name: ~Slug }                           # digit | alpha | alnum | ws | ...
form Run          = { name: ~Slug }                           # one-or-more of a class → a slice
form Ref⟨grammar⟩ = { rule: ~Slug }                           # name of a peer rule
form Seq          = [ Pattern ]                               # ordered children
form Alt          = [ Pattern ]                               # ordered alternatives
form Opt          = { inner: Pattern }
form Rep          = { inner: Pattern, sep: Opt⟨Pattern⟩, min: ~Integer }
form Capture      = { name: ~Slug, inner: Pattern }
form Pred         = { sense: ~Bool, inner: Pattern }          # &p (and), !p (not)
form Infix        = { operand: Pattern, table: [ { op: ~String, bp: ~Slug, prec: ~Integer } ] }
form Chain        = { base: Pattern, expr: Pattern }          # the suffix fold; expr = how args/indices parse
form Ternary      = { cond: Pattern, branch: Pattern }
```

`Alt` is `choose` at the parse altitude; `Pred` is angelic lookahead; `Rep`'s
separator handles comma-lists without a special rule. Every arm is itself a
recipe whose children are recipes — the Pattern tree is a recipe tree.

`Infix`, `Chain`, and `Ternary` are the **high-level folds**, and they are why
there is **no result-stack**. Classic BMF accumulates matches on an imperative
ResultStack (push on match, pop+reduce in a container) because production and
consumption are decoupled in time. Here each rule *returns* its built node and
its parent composes it on the return path — `Infix` folds a precedence ladder,
`Chain` folds `a.b.c().d[i]` left into universal access/call nodes, `Ternary`
builds `UE-COND-TERNARY` — so the recursion's reduction **is** the stack. The
native call stack carries what the explicit ResultStack used to.

Where the core primitives stand, named honestly: **fail + undo** are grounded —
the cursor is immutable, so a failed branch costs nothing to abandon (`Alt`
hands the *same* cursor to the next arm; do/undo are the same coordinate).
**choice** (`Alt`) and the pattern **switch** in `Match` are correct but still
expressed as fk-level recursion + a linear tag test; the kernel already
dispatches its *own* execution by NodeID in O(1), so the open grounding is to
lift pattern-kind to a Blueprint and make `Match` dispatch through that same
O(1) NodeID switch — *switch is free* — rather than re-deriving it with a tag
chain. That is a kernel-native step, named here so the next cell can take it.

### Observability — the cursor's furthest reach

A failed `Alt` returns the *pre*-failure cursor (no-sediment backtracking), so a
partial parse silently rewinds and the caller can't see where the grammar gave
out. The fix is to let the cursor carry its **furthest reach**: the deepest
stream position any rule was attempted at, and that rule's name. Probing the
four thesis `.bml` files with this proved its worth — it pinpointed the frontier
at byte 6328 (a `catch` body), which named the real gap: a local declaration
*without* initializer (`ParseStream hStream;` — only `Type name = expr;` was a
rule). Adding `declnoinit` advanced the frontier to byte 15941 of 15943, and Go
and TS then fully parsed all four files.

Two design notes the proving exposed:
- **Keep it cheap or opt-in.** Tracking it with `record_get`/`record_set` on
  *every* rule entry (each interning the field name) made the hot path far
  slower under heavy backtracking — Rust went from finishing to minutes. The
  frontier wants a single mutable int cell updated only on a strict advance, or
  a tracking mode toggled off for production parses.
- **It surfaces the real frontier: backtracking cost.** With the deep parse
  unlocked, the grammar's PEG backtracking is the wall — the same `(rule, pos)`
  is re-parsed across `Alt` branches and `Chain` arg-exprs, multiplying through
  expression depth. This is the twin of
  the O(1)-switch grounding: **packrat memoization** — cache `(rule, pos) →
  result`, turning exponential re-descent into linear. It IS the body's own
  teaching that *repeated observation condenses to one result* (gas→water→ice,
  JIT). The one constraint: memo identity is per-input — key it by the surface
  (or give each parse a fresh memo), since grammars are reused across inputs.
  Linear parsing is what lets the 4th file complete on every kernel and lets the
  furthest-reach cell run always-on without cost.

**The bottleneck is the interpreter, not re-parsing — measured, and it corrects
the earlier guess.** I built a *real* O(1) content-addressed parse-cache (a Go
`map[NodeID]Value` native, `cache_new`/`cache_get`/`cache_set` — not the linear
`record`), wired packrat into `g-match-rule` (fresh cache per parse, key =
interned `(rule, pos)` NodeID), and pointed it at the four thesis files. The
result overturns the condensation story:

```
Go, all four files (decl-noinit on):  no cache 18.2s   with O(1) cache 17.8s
```

Packrat makes **no difference**. The cost is not the same `(rule, pos)` being
re-parsed across `Alt` branches — so caching it saves nothing. A CPU sample says
why: **~all time is in `main.(*Kernel).walk`** — the fk interpreter's tree-walk.
The grammar runs as *interpreted fk*; every `g-match`, every `str_eq` tag test,
every `cons`/`if`/`let` is a `walk` step, and there are millions of them.

**The Rust wall was memory, not speed — fixed (cross-kernel 2222 shipped, #2514).**
Rust did not hang on a slow interpreter; it OOM'd at 242 GB on the 15 KB file
where Go used ~10 MB. Two carrier bugs, both *holding the past you no longer
need*: (1) `Value::Str`/`List` deep-cloned on every `clone()`, and the cursor —
which embeds the whole source string — is threaded through every call, so each
parse step deep-copied the file (fix: `Arc<str>` / `Arc<Vec<Value>>`, so clone is
a refcount bump, matching Go's shared slice/string backing); (2) the arena pushed
a `Frame` per call and never reclaimed it *during* eval, where Go's GC frees
`*Frame`s the moment they go unreachable (fix: the `walk` wrapper truncates frames
on return, guarded by *no closure was created during the call* — a closure is the
only `Value` that captures a `FrameId`, so otherwise every frame above the entry
mark is provably dead). Result: **18–21 MB flat regardless of input; the full
file parses to EOF in 19 MB**, and the realfiles band is Go = Rust = TS = 2222.
This is the body's own teaching made literal in the carrier — *hold only now (the
cursor) and the trusted result, release the derivation*. The interpreter speed
below is real and orthogonal: it is now a *speed* lever (the JIT), no longer a
*completion* wall.

So the lever is not condensation, and it is *not* hand-porting a native Match
into Go/Rust/TS — that would fork the engine out of Form and break *"the only
code is Match + Cursor + primitives; everything else is data."* The engine
**stays Form recipes**. Nothing decrees that Form is *interpreted* — the
interpreter (`walk`) is just the JIT's current ceiling. The real lever is the
**JIT**: it already compiles Form recipes → native (`jit.go`: recipe → Go via
`go build -buildmode=plugin`), and the architecture's intent is that it compile
*any* recipe. Today it compiles an **int64-only** subset (trivials, MATH,
COMPARE, COND, BLOCK, self-recursion) and *refuses* lists, strings, native
calls, and non-int signatures — which is exactly why the grammar engine's
recipes (`str_eq`, `cons`, `intern_node`, `cur-peek`, recursion over lists/
nodes) fall back to `walk`. **Extend the JIT from int64-only to `Value`-typed
with native-call emission**, and the *same* Form engine (`g-match` and friends),
JIT-compiled, becomes native — no fork, grammars still data, the kernel still
thin. That is what turns 18s into milliseconds and lets Rust complete. Cut and a
left-factored grammar are second-order gains on top.

**Second experiment — Cut (the thesis's own tool), and why it ranks above
packrat.** The thesis BMF engine had a `Cut` primitive (`primitive-Cut.bml`):
once a rule's discriminator matches, *cut* commits and the enclosing choice
never tries the other alternatives. That attacks a different axis than packrat —
packrat caches *re-evaluation*; cut prevents *first-time evaluation of doomed
alternatives*. I implemented committed-choice (a `(cut)` pattern; failures after
a cut propagate up through seq/rep/sep/opt to the nearest `Alt`, which stops),
placed cut after the unique keyword discriminators (if/for/while/switch/try/…),
and measured:

```
Go, all four files:   no cut 18.2s    with cut 9.3s   (~2x, interpreted)
```

So cut *works* where packrat didn't — it prunes the exploration space, exactly
as it did on 2000-era hardware. Two honest caveats: (1) the 9.3s isn't pure
speedup — cut also flipped BMF-grammar.bml from `2` to `1`, revealing that its
prior "full parse" leaned on imprecise backtracking that consumed to EOF without
correctly parsing every construct; cut enforces honest coverage. (2) cut at the
*keyword* level only prunes cheap-doomed alternatives; the expensive doomed ones
(decl/assign/expr sharing a leading construct) need the grammar *left-factored*
so a cut can commit after that shared construct.

**Ranked, measured:** packrat — no help (wrong axis). Cut — ~2x and the thesis's
proven lever, but needs left-factoring + honest-coverage repair to land.
**JIT-compiling the Form engine** — the big multiplier (the thesis was *compiled*
Java, not interpreted; that, plus cut, is why old hardware ran it trivially). The
real target is **JIT the engine recipes + cut + a left-factored grammar**
together — each was one leg of why the thesis was fast, and we'd been missing all
three. The engine stays Form; the JIT (not a hand-port) makes it native.

**Third experiment — reshape the grammar itself (full freedom granted).** With
license to change any grammar shape for efficiency, I flattened: inlined the thin
`orexpr` wrapper into `expr` (one fewer rule-dispatch per operand) and reordered
`primary` so the common operand — an identifier — matches in 2 alt-tries instead
of 5 (with `litnum` kept first, since `ident`'s alnum-run also matches digits —
a reorder that looked free but would have silently parsed numbers as identifiers,
and the consume-metric wouldn't have caught it). Measured, same coverage:

```
Go, BMF-grammar prefix workload:   baseline 8.45s    flattened 7.80s   (~8%)
```

So grammar reshape is **real but small (~8%)**, and the packrat result already
told us why: the cost isn't re-parsing or wide alt-exploration — it's the *single*
deep parse of every operand, interpreted. The ladder's loops already live in
engine combinators (`infix`/`chain`/`ternary`); the fk-rule overhead that's left
is a handful of dispatches per token, and shaving them buys ~8%, not 8×.

**The settled conclusion, evidenced across four experiments** (packrat 0 %, cut
~2× but coverage-confounded, flatten ~8 %, profile = ~all in `walk`): *the BML
grammar is not the bottleneck — the interpreter is.* The grammar is already
about as token- and shape-efficient as interpretation rewards; the multiplier is
to **JIT-compile the Form engine** so `Match` stops running through `walk` —
the engine stays Form recipes, the JIT turns them native (the thesis's compiled
engine, reached the substrate's own way), with cut and a left-factored grammar
as second-order gains. The concrete build: extend `jit.go` from its current
int64-only subset to **`Value`-typed codegen with native-call emission**, so the
engine recipes (`str_eq`/`cons`/`intern_node`/`cur-*`/recursion) compile instead
of falling back to `walk`. Each grammar experiment was honest and cheap;
together they rule out the grammar as the lever and point, with evidence, at the
JIT.

### The JIT unlock — verified mechanism + the cross-kernel build

Goal: *any* recipe → a native plugin, on every kernel. The blocker and the fix
are now verified on this machine (darwin/arm64, go1.26.3), not assumed:

- **`buildmode=plugin` works on macOS** — built a `.so`, `plugin.Open` + call →
  correct; the kernel's own `go-jit-band` scores its full verdict here. (No
  Linux dependency — an earlier "flaky on macOS" claim was false.)
- **The real constraint:** a plugin is itself `package main`, so it cannot import
  the kernel's `main`-package `Value`/`Kernel`/`NodeID`. *That* is why the
  current JIT is int64-only (int64 is a builtin, needs no kernel types).
- **The fix, shipped (Go):** the kernel's core types live in a **shared importable
  package** (`form-kernel-go/core`); the kernel binary and every plugin import it.
  `jit_value.go` compiles ANY recipe to a `core.Value`-typed plugin — strings,
  lists, native calls, cross-function calls all flow; a `dispatch` callback routes
  every native / other-function call back to the kernel's registry; self-recursion
  stays a native `self()` call. Proven end-to-end: a recipe with a string arg +
  three native calls (`str_len`/`char_at`/`ord`) + recursion returns the walker's
  exact answer (`jit_value_test.go`), and runs **~3.8× faster** than `walk` on an
  11M-call native-heavy workload (fib(33): walk ~6.0s → JIT-exec ~1.6s); the
  one-time `go build` (~0.9s) is cached per body-NodeID thereafter.

**The build (incremental, cross-kernel-safe — JIT is transparent: a recipe is
JIT-compiled or walked, same result, so each kernel lands independently and
`validate` still agrees):**

1. **Go — DONE.** `core` package extracted from `main`; `jit_value.go` emits
   `core.Value`-typed plugins (trivials → typed Values; `if`/`do`/`let`/`and`/`or`
   → Go control flow over Values, faithful to Form's frame-scoped `let`; native &
   cross-function calls → `dispatch(nameID, args)`; self-recursion → `self(...)`).
   The `jit_compile_value` native compiles + caches per body-NodeID; FNCALL
   dispatch prefers the Value plugin, falls back to `walk` for unlowerable shapes.

   **Engine JIT'd + benchmarked on the real thesis files (measured):** 145 of the
   146 engine recipes (`g-match-rule`, `gm-*`, `cur-*`, `match-*`, `is-*`, …) lower
   to native plugins (1 shape unsupported → walk); the JIT'd parse of all four real
   `.bml` files scores **2221, identical to walked**. Speed: **~1.45×** (walked
   11.4s/parse → JIT'd 7.8s/parse, 20-iter avg; one-time compile ~121s, cached).

   *Why 1.45× here vs ~3.8× on clean compute:* the recursive-descent engine is
   leaf-call-dominated (`cur-peek`, `str_eq`, `head`/`tail`/`cons`/`nth`,
   `char_at`), and every leaf still pays a **dispatch hop** (`callValueByName`: map
   lookups + env shadow-checks). JIT-ing the control-flow glue is done; the hop is
   now the bottleneck. **Next lever (evidence-identified):** inline the hot natives
   directly as Go over `core.Value` in the codegen (skip dispatch for the hottest
   leaves), and resolve native-vs-closure at emit time so a native call emits a
   direct registry call rather than a name lookup. Then re-benchmark.
2. **Rust** — core types already separable into a lib crate; emit a `cdylib`,
   load via `libloading`, same `Value`-typed contract.
3. **TypeScript** — emit JS for the recipe and `import()` it dynamically (or
   compile to WASM); "native" here = run as host JS, off the `walk` interpreter.

The first milestone (Go) is met: `core` extracted, a Value-typed JIT compiling
recipes with native calls, benchmarked ~3.8× over `walk`. The multiplier is real;
widening it to the whole engine (then Rust/TS) is what takes the interpreted ~8s
toward milliseconds, with cut and a left-factored grammar composing on top.

### Template blueprints — the emitting side

```form
# A Template, given the captures a Pattern bound, builds one output recipe.
form Template = ~Sum [
    Emit,            # build a node: a universal category + arm + children
    Splice,          # insert a captured sub-node (or list) by name
    Const,           # a literal leaf (string / int / bool)
    Fold,            # fold a captured list into a chain (left/right assoc)
]

form Emit   = { shape: ~Category, arm: ~Slug, children: [ Template ] }
form Splice = { name: ~Slug, list: ~Bool }            # `x` or `x*`
form Const  = { value: ~Any }
form Fold   = { dir: ~Assoc, shape: ~Category, arm: ~Slug, over: ~Slug }
```

The Template is the *only* place a grammar names the **output** vocabulary. Two
grammars that emit the same `Emit{shape, arm, …}` produce the same output
coordinate — that is how cross-language equivalence is free.

### Rule and Grammar blueprints — the bag

```form
# Generic over its pattern and template — a rule is a rule in any grammar.
form Rule⟨P: Pattern, T: Template⟩ = {
    name:     ~Slug,
    pattern:  P,
    template: T,
}

form Grammar = {
    name:    ~Slug,
    start:   ~Slug,            # entry rule
    rules:   [ Rule ],         # the bag — order is for humans; dispatch is by coordinate
    config:  Config,           # data, below
    target:  Vocabulary,       # the output Blueprint family this grammar emits into
}
```

A `Grammar` is a cell whose CTOR is the sequence of its rules. Registering a
grammar is interning that cell — idempotent by content-addressing.

### Cursor blueprint — generic over the surface

```form
# The input stream, generic over any surface. The surface is a Port; the
# Cursor presents one interface (a BML detached interface) over all of them.
form Cursor⟨S: Surface⟩ = { surface: S, pos: ~Position }

# Surface is satisfied by any port that can answer peek/advance/checkpoint.
# These are the ONLY host touch-points the engine needs:
view Surface = {
    peek:       (self, n)        -> ~Token,      # look ahead, no consume
    advance:    (self, n)        -> Cursor,      # returns a NEW cursor (no mutation)
    checkpoint: (self)           -> ~Position,   # for backtracking
    restore:    (self, ~Position)-> Cursor,      # do/undo are symmetric here
}

# Surfaces — all share the Cursor interface:
form File⟨⟩    = { path: ~Path }
form Strng⟨⟩   = { text: ~String }
form Socket⟨⟩  = { conn: ~Conn }
form Cell⟨⟩    = { id:   ~NodeID }     # iterate a cell's children / serialized form
form Channel⟨⟩ = { path: ~Path }       # the CHANNEL-V0 recipe transport
```

`advance` returns a *new* cursor rather than mutating — so a checkpoint is just
holding an old cursor coordinate, and restore is dropping back to it. Backtracking
costs nothing to undo because nothing was changed.

### Universal output blueprints — the shared shapes (NUMS.Go)

```form
# What every grammar's Template emits INTO. Never language-prefixed.
~Function   = @1.4.B_FUNCTION       # a function in any tongue
~Call       = R_Call                # application
~Binary(op) = R_Binary              # + - * / and/or/eq/...  (op is the arm)
~Cond(op)   = R_Cond                # IF / IF_ELSE / MATCH
~Block(op)  = R_Block               # DO / LET / SEQ / WITH
~Loop(op)   = R_Loop                # WHILE / FOR / EACH
```

A Python `def`, a Go `func`, a Rust `fn` all emit `~Function` — one coordinate.
The grammar carries the surface words; the lattice carries the meaning.

## The core recipe — `Match`

```form
# THE engine. One recipe, generic over (Grammar, Cursor). Pure: cursor in,
# (nodes, cursor') out, or fail. No mutation, so every sub-match is cacheable.
recipe Match⟨G: Grammar, C: Cursor⟩ = (grammar, cursor) -> {
    rule = grammar.rule(grammar.start)             # O(1) coordinate lookup
    match_rule(rule, cursor)
}

recipe match_rule = (rule, cursor) ->
    # memoized on (rule.id, cursor.pos) — packrat for free via content-addressing
    with match_pattern(rule.pattern, cursor) {
        on success(captures, cursor') ->
            success( build(rule.template, captures), cursor' )   # emit the node
        on fail -> fail                                          # restore caller's cursor
    }

recipe match_pattern = (pattern, cursor) -> choose_by_arm pattern {
    Literal  -> if cursor.starts_with(pattern.chars) then ok(cursor.advance(len)) else fail
    Class    -> if class_has(pattern.name, cursor.peek()) then ok(cursor.advance(1)) else fail
    Run      -> consume while class_has(pattern.name, cursor.peek())   # ≥1 char, else fail
    Ref      -> match_rule(grammar.rule(pattern.rule), cursor)
    Seq      -> fold parts: thread the cursor; first fail fails the Seq
    Alt      -> choose [ match_pattern(a, cursor) for a in pattern ]   # parallel-able
    Opt      -> match_pattern(inner) orElse ok(cursor)                 # never fails
    Rep      -> loop match(inner); collect into a list; honor sep + min
    Capture  -> bind pattern.name := result(match_pattern(inner))
    Pred     -> match without advancing; sense flips success/fail
}

recipe build = (template, captures) -> choose_by_arm template {
    Emit   -> intern( node(template.shape, template.arm,
                           [ build(c, captures) for c in template.children ]) )
    Splice -> captures[template.name]                 # already a NodeID
    Const  -> intern_leaf(template.value)
    Fold   -> fold(template.dir, captures[template.over],
                   (a, b) -> intern(node(template.shape, template.arm, [a, b])))
}
```

`Match` is the same whether `grammar` is the meta-grammar or a content grammar.
`Alt` is the parse-time `choose`; `build`'s `intern` is the dedup that makes the
whole thing content-addressed and JIT-able.

## The self-hosting fixpoint — the meta-grammar is a grammar

The meta-grammar `M` is a `Grammar` whose **target vocabulary is the grammar
vocabulary itself** — its Templates emit `Pattern`, `Template`, `Rule`, and
`Grammar` recipes. Therefore:

```
M : Grammar
Match(M, Cursor(grammar_source)) : Grammar        # output is a Grammar
```

The type is closed under itself. The meta-grammar parses the very notation the
next section defines, and what it emits is a runnable grammar. There is no
second engine, no separate "compiler for grammars" — the compiler-compiler is
`Match` reading `M`.

## The two applications — minimal bootstrap to native

```form
# 1. Bootstrap: the meta-grammar arrives already interned, frozen in a .fkb
#    image from a previous iteration. Loading it is NOT parsing — it is
#    reconstituting cells (bulk registration from a content-addressed image).
meta = load_fkb("bmf-meta.fkb")                    # the compiler-compiler, ice

# 2. Compile a content grammar from its source, using the meta-grammar:
python = Match(meta, Cursor(File("grammars/python.bmf")))    # → a native Grammar

# 3. Run the native grammar on real input, over ANY surface:
nodes = Match(python, Cursor(File("app.py")))
nodes = Match(python, Cursor(Strng(src_text)))
nodes = Match(python, Cursor(Socket(conn)))
nodes = Match(python, Cursor(Channel("/tmp/in.fkb")))
```

The bootstrap is exactly one frozen artifact: `bmf-meta.fkb`. Everything past it
is parsed by the meta-grammar. Lose the `.fkb` and you can rebuild it by running
the previous meta on the meta's own source (the BMC ratchet) — but you never
*need* to, because the image is the body's memory of its own compiler.

## Surface syntax — BMF's own notation, kept from the 2000 thesis

A grammar is a list of **rules**. A rule reads
`NAME [ ( params ) ] ::= PATTERN [ => TEMPLATE ] ;`. The **matching side** (`::=` …)
is kept verbatim from the thesis BMF — the same `::=`, `{ }`, `[ ]`, `< >`, `|`,
`$tag:`, `\\`, and parameterized `Name( … )` that BMF used to declare itself in
2000. The `=> TEMPLATE` seam is the one addition (explained after the example).

```bmf
# ── PATTERN — the matching side (thesis-faithful) ────────────
#   "lit"              literal characters                        (CharChain)
#   < 'a'..'z' | '_' > one char in a range/set ( ..=range |=or )  (Terminal)
#   NAME               reference another rule (recursion)         (RuleCall)
#   NAME( a, b )       parameterized / template rule              (e.g. List(item, sep))
#   $tag:p             capture p under `tag`                      (Tag)
#   a  b  c            sequence — all in order                    (AND-list)
#   a | b              branch — first that holds                  (OR-list)
#   { p }              zero-or-more        [ p ]  optional         (Repeat)
#   p \\ sep           p separated by sep   ≡  p { sep p }        (runtime-added construct)
#   ( … )              grouping
#   cut  fail  EOF  EOL  primitives: commit / backtrack / stream edges
#
# ── TEMPLATE — the emitting side (the one addition) ──────────
#   ~Shape(arm)[ … ]   emit a node of the UNIVERSAL category Shape, arm, children
#   tag                splice the captured node `tag`       tag*  splice the list
#   #"text"            a literal leaf
#   fold.left ~Bin     fold a captured list into a left-assoc chain

# A slice of Python, in the thesis notation:
grammar python over chars {
  start ::= module ;

  add  ::= mul { ( "+" | "-" ) mul }               => fold.left ~Binary(op) ;
  call ::= $callee:atom "(" $arg:expr \\ "," ")"   => ~Call[ callee, arg* ] ;
  if   ::= "if" $cond:expr ":" $body:block
             [ "else" ":" $else:block ]            => ~Cond(IF)[ cond, body, else? ] ;
  func ::= "def" $name:ID "(" $param:ID \\ "," ")" ":" $body:block
                                                   => ~Function[ #name, param*, body ] ;
  ID   ::= < 'a'..'z' | 'A'..'Z' | '_' >
           < 'a'..'z' | 'A'..'Z' | '0'..'9' | '_' >* ;
}
```

**What stayed and what changed from the thesis.** Everything left of `=>` is the
thesis verbatim: `Number ::= < '0'..'9' > [ '.' < '0'..'9' > ];` and
`List( item, sep ) ::= item { sep item };` parse unchanged. The thesis attached
the *action* as a separate `#process` METHOD that rewrote the parse tree after a
rule completed. Here the action is inline **data** — `=> ~Shape[…]` — a template
that emits into the universal recipe vocabulary. Two consequences: the action is
content-addressed (the same emit shape from any grammar is one NodeID) and shared,
not host code; and the thesis read a `ParseStream` over a file, where the cursor
reads any surface. Otherwise the surface a human writes is the 2000 surface.

### The notation describes itself — BMF-in-BMF

The meta-grammar is a grammar in exactly this notation; its templates emit
`Rule` / `Pattern` / `Template` recipes — the shapes `Match` consumes. The
self-hosting fixpoint, made literal:

```bmf
grammar bmf over chars {
  start    ::= { rule } ;

  rule     ::= $name:NAME [ "(" $params:NAME \\ "," ")" ] "::=" $pat:pattern
                 [ "=>" $tpl:template ] ";"        => ~Rule[ name, params*, pat, tpl? ] ;

  pattern  ::= alt ;
  alt      ::= seq { "|" seq }                      => fold ~Alt ;
  seq      ::= postfix+                             => ~Seq[ postfix* ] ;
  postfix  ::= $p:primary [ "*" | "+" | "?" ]       => ~Rep[ p ] | ~Opt[ p ] | p ;
  primary  ::= literal | range | capture | seplist | group | ruleref ;

  literal  ::= '"' < any-but-quote >* '"'           => ~Literal[ chars ] ;
  range    ::= "<" charset \\ "|" ">"               => ~Class[ charset* ] ;
  charset  ::= $lo:CHAR [ ".." $hi:CHAR ]           => ~Range[ lo, hi? ] ;
  capture  ::= "$" $tag:NAME ":" $p:primary         => ~Capture[ tag, p ] ;
  seplist  ::= $p:primary "\\" $sep:primary         => ~SepRep[ p, sep ] ;
  group    ::= "(" pattern ")"                      => pattern ;
  ruleref  ::= $r:NAME [ "(" pattern \\ "," ")" ]   => ~Ref[ r, args* ] ;

  template ::= "~" $shape:NAME [ "(" $arm:NAME ")" ]
                 [ "[" arg \\ "," "]" ]             => ~Emit[ shape, arm?, args* ] ;
  arg      ::= template | splice | const ;
  splice   ::= $tag:NAME [ "*" ]                     => ~Splice[ tag, list? ] ;
  const    ::= "#" literal                           => ~Const[ literal ] ;

  NAME     ::= < 'a'..'z' | 'A'..'Z' | '_' >
               < 'a'..'z' | 'A'..'Z' | '0'..'9' | '_' | '-' >* ;
}
```

Run this grammar over its own source through `Match` and it emits the
`Rule` / `Pattern` / `Template` recipes that *are* a grammar — the body's
compiler-compiler, frozen into `bmf-meta.fkb` so the bootstrap need never expand
again. (The data shapes in [`bmf-core.fk`](../../form/form-stdlib/bmf-core.fk) —
`lit` / `cls` / `run` / `seq` / `alt` / `opt` / `cap` — are what this surface
compiles *to*; the surface is the thesis, the interned recipes are the lattice.)

## Configuration and registration as data

```form
form Config = {
    precedence: [ OpPrec ],       # operator table — DATA, not a hardcoded ladder
    target:     Vocabulary,       # which universal Blueprint family to emit into
    surfaces:   [ ~SurfaceKind ], # which cursor surfaces this grammar accepts
}
form OpPrec = { op: ~String, prec: ~Integer, assoc: ~Assoc }
```

- **There is no lexer — the grammar is scannerless.** Patterns match *characters*
  directly over the cursor: `Class` / `Run` consume character classes, `Literal`
  matches an exact string, all through `peek` / `advance`. What a lexer would do is
  just ordinary patterns in the one grammar — no token stream, no tokenize phase.
  (A token *layer* is an optional optimization, not a component: if you ever want
  shared tokens, run the same `Match` over a char-cursor to emit token-cells that a
  second `Match` consumes. Same engine, never a special phase.)
- **Precedence is a table of cells**, read by the `add`/`mul`-style rules (or by a
  single precedence-climbing rule parameterized by the table). Change precedence
  = edit data, never code.
- **Registration = intern.** `register(rule)` interns the rule's cell into the
  `grammar` domain; same rule twice → same NodeID (idempotent). `load_fkb` is
  bulk registration from a frozen image. There is no mutable global registry to
  corrupt; the lattice *is* the registry.

## What coordinates buy the engine

- **O(1) rule dispatch** — `grammar.rule(name)` is a coordinate lookup; `Alt` and
  `choose_by_arm` are coordinate switches, not scans.
- **Parallel `Alt`** — alternatives share no mutable state, so they can be matched
  on separate threads; first success commits, the rest collapse (`fail`).
- **Packrat for free** — `match_rule(rule, pos)` memoizes on `(rule.id, pos)`;
  content-addressing gives the cache key with no bookkeeping. Linear-time parse
  is a side effect of the substrate, not an algorithm bolted on.
- **Symmetric backtrack** — a checkpoint is an old cursor coordinate; restore is
  dropping to it. `do` and `undo` cost the same.
- **Observation → JIT** — hot `match_rule` results and hot emitted shapes condense
  (gas → water → ice). The framebuffer watches which rules and shapes fire most;
  the hot path compiles itself.
- **Dimension lowering** — every re-encountered sub-tree interns to the same
  coordinate, so parsing the same construct twice costs one node plus a count.
  The grammar's output compresses as the corpus grows.

## Meeting the body — what exists, the deltas, the staged path

This is the reconciliation written *after* looking at the current implementation.

**What the body holds today.** The engine is `apply-object-rule` in
[`form/form-stdlib/engine.fk`](../../form/form-stdlib/engine.fk) — pure-functional,
with pattern constructors (`object`, `sequence`, `choice`, `capture`, `star`,
`opt`, `cut`, `stop`) and `cut` for backtrack pruning. It is elegant. But:

- **Input is a pre-built object list**, not a cursor. A sensing layer outside Form
  (a kernel-native `ast.parse`, tree-sitter, …) turns bytes into BMF objects; the
  engine only consumes the list. There is no cursor over a surface.
- **A rule's action is a hand-written Form lambda** (`gobmf-emit-package`) paired
  with a hand-written reverse lambda — per rule, per language. Code, not data.
- **Grammars emit to per-language categories** (`GO-BMF-*`, `PY-BMF-*`), not always
  to the universal vocabulary — the unresolved "CTOR unification."
- **The meta-grammar is a hand-written line-scanner** (`source-compiler.fk` parsing
  `section [dialect] { … }`), not itself a grammar.
- **The `.fkb` ratchet is metadata-only** — it records compiler-image identity but
  carries no executable payload yet.

**The four deltas this architecture adds**, each matching a named pain point:

| Delta | Replaces | Pain point |
|---|---|---|
| Cursor over surfaces | the external object-list sensing gap | (new keystone) |
| Template as data (`Emit`/`Splice`/`Const`/`Fold`) | per-rule emit/reverse lambdas | engine.fk #1, #2 |
| Universal emit always (`bp op`) | per-dialect categories | CTOR unification #4 |
| Self-hosted meta-grammar | `source-compiler.fk` line-scanner | #5 |

**What landed this breath** ([`form/form-stdlib/bmf-core.fk`](../../form/form-stdlib/bmf-core.fk),
proven by [`form/form-stdlib/tests/bmf-core-band.fk`](../../form/form-stdlib/tests/bmf-core-band.fk)
→ `600`, `1 ok, 0 divergent` across Go/Rust/TS): the keystone and two of the four
deltas, on a minimal worked example —

- a **Cursor** over a string surface (file wired via `read_file`; socket/cell/channel
  are the next surfaces), with pure `peek` / `advance` / `checkpoint` / `restore`;
- **Pattern as data** (`lit`/`cls`/`run`/`seq`/`alt`/`opt`/`cap`) driven by one matcher,
  with `alt` backtracking proven to leave no sediment (the source cursor is unchanged);
- **Template as data** (`emit`/`splice`/`const`) built by one interpreter that emits
  into the **universal** vocabulary, proven to land `digits "+" digits` on the same
  `add` coordinate as a hand-built node.

**The staged path (next breaths), in order:**

1. **Migrate the language grammars** to `(pattern, template)` data rules over the
   cursor; retire the per-rule emit/reverse lambdas. (engine.fk #2, #3) — *the
   recursive engine is shipped:* [`bmf-grammar.fk`](../../form/form-stdlib/bmf-grammar.fk)
   adds named rules + `ref`/recursion + `rep`/`sep` list-capture + node-captures
   (the two primitives the slice once lacked). Full **BML**, **Go**, and **Java**
   method grammars now parse real source into universal trees and converge on one
   `~fndef` — [`grammars-from-the-cursor.form`](grammars-from-the-cursor.form)
   (`bmf-grammar-band`/`bml-band`/`lang-convergence-band` each → 300). BML templates
   + generics are in too (`bml-generics-band → 300`: generic types as `~fncall`,
   template classes + generic methods capture type params). Remaining: Python/Rust/C#
   full grammars — rule-data, not engine.
2. **Universal-emit-always** — every template emits `(bp <universal-op>)`; retire the
   per-dialect category numbers. (#4)
3. **Self-host the meta-grammar** — express the grammar-definition notation (the
   `NAME : PATTERN => TEMPLATE` of the Surface-syntax section) as a grammar whose
   templates emit `Rule`/`Pattern`/`Template` recipes; retire `source-compiler.fk`. (#5)
4. **Freeze `bmf-meta.fkb`** with an executable payload, so the compiler-compiler
   loads from the image and the bootstrap goes archival. (compiler-picture Next Refinement #1)
5. **Streaming surfaces** — socket / cell / channel cursors with incremental peek,
   completing the dream's full surface set.

Each is its own breath; this one laid the cursor and the data-driven match/emit.

## The one-line shape

> **A grammar is a bag of (Pattern ⇒ Template) rules; `Match` drives a Cursor
> over any surface through that bag, interning one recipe per rule into the
> universal vocabulary. The meta-grammar is the grammar whose Templates emit
> grammars — so the compiler-compiler is `Match` reading a frozen `.fkb` of
> itself, and everything else is data.**
